Machine Learning: AllLife Bank Personal Loan Campaign¶

Problem Statement¶

Context¶

AllLife Bank is a US bank that has a growing customer base. The majority of these customers are liability customers (depositors) with varying sizes of deposits. The number of customers who are also borrowers (asset customers) is quite small, and the bank is interested in expanding this base rapidly to bring in more loan business and in the process, earn more through the interest on loans. In particular, the management wants to explore ways of converting its liability customers to personal loan customers (while retaining them as depositors).

A campaign that the bank ran last year for liability customers showed a healthy conversion rate of over 9% success. This has encouraged the retail marketing department to devise campaigns with better target marketing to increase the success ratio.

You as a Data scientist at AllLife bank have to build a model that will help the marketing department to identify the potential customers who have a higher probability of purchasing the loan.

Objective¶

To predict whether a liability customer will buy personal loans, to understand which customer attributes are most significant in driving purchases, and identify which segment of customers to target more.

Data Dictionary¶

  • ID: Customer ID
  • Age: Customers age in completed years
  • Experience: #years of professional experience
  • Income: Annual income of the customer (in thousand dollars)
  • ZIP Code: Home Address ZIP code.
  • Family: the Family size of the customer
  • CCAvg: Average spending on credit cards per month (in thousand dollars)
  • Education: Education Level. 1: Undergrad; 2: Graduate;3: Advanced/Professional
  • Mortgage: Value of house mortgage if any. (in thousand dollars)
  • Personal_Loan: Did this customer accept the personal loan offered in the last campaign? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Securities_Account: Does the customer have securities account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CD_Account: Does the customer have a certificate of deposit (CD) account with the bank? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • Online: Do customers use internet banking facilities? (0: No, 1: Yes)
  • CreditCard: Does the customer use a credit card issued by any other Bank (excluding All life Bank)? (0: No, 1: Yes)

How does a customer's interest in purchasing a loan vary with their age?

In [117]:
# create age bins
bins = [18,25,35,45,55,65,100]
labels = ['18-25', '26-35', '36-45', '46-55','56-65','66+']
loan_data['AgeGroup'] = pd.cut(loan_data['Age'], bins=bins, labels=labels, include_lowest = True)

# calculate percentage of customers who took a personal loan in each age group
loan_count = loan_data.groupby('AgeGroup')['Personal_Loan'].sum()

# plot the results
plt.figure(figsize=(8,6))
loan_count.plot(kind = 'bar')
plt.xlabel ('Age Group')
plt.ylabel ('Number of Customers who took a Personal Loan')
plt.title('Interest in Loans by Age')
plt.xticks(rotation=45)
plt.show()

Observations:

  • The age group of 26-35 have the highest number of loans taken.
  • 18-25 years old have not taken any loans.
  • I don't think age affects a customer's interest in taking a loan because all the age groups take loans and there isn't a specific pattern here.

# Split Data

from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import OneHotEncoder


# Split data into features (X) and target (y)
X = loan_data.drop(['Personal_Loan'], axis=1)
y = loan_data['Personal_Loan']

# convert age_group to categorical type

X['AgeGroup'] = X['AgeGroup'].astype('category')

# One-hot encode AgeGroup
encoder = OneHotEncoder(handle_unknown='ignore')
X_encoded = pd.DataFrame(encoder.fit_transform(X[['AgeGroup']]).toarray(), columns=encoder.get_feature_names_out(['AgeGroup']))

# Drop the original AgeGroup column and concatenate with the encoded columns
X = pd.concat([X.drop('AgeGroup', axis=1), X_encoded], axis=1)



# Split data into training and testing sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=0.30, random_state=42)


# Check if the data is split correctly

# create function for decision rules

def get_decision_rules(tree, feature_names, class_names, node_index=0, path=[]):
    tree_ = tree.tree_
    feature = [feature_names[i] for i in tree_.feature]

    # If the node is a leaf node
    if tree_.children_left[node_index] == -1 and tree_.children_right[node_index] == -1:
        rule = ' AND '.join(path)
        class_id = np.argmax(tree_.value[node_index][0])
        class_name = class_names[class_id]
        print(f"IF {rule} THEN Personal_Loan = {class_name}")
        return

    # If the node is an internal node
    threshold = tree_.threshold[node_index]
    feature_name = feature[node_index]

    # go on the left subtree
    new_path = path + [f"{feature_name} <= {threshold}"]
    get_decision_rules(tree, feature_names, class_names, tree_.children_left[node_index], new_path)

    # go on the right subtree
    new_path = path + [f"{feature_name} > {threshold}"]
    get_decision_rules(tree, feature_names, class_names, tree_.children_right[node_index], new_path)

# Call the function
get_decision_rules(dt_classifier, feature_names, class_names)

Post-Pruning Model¶

In [138]:
from sklearn.tree import DecisionTreeClassifier, plot_tree, export_graphviz
from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Train the base (unpruned) decision tree model
dt_classifier = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42)
dt_classifier.fit(X_train, y_train)

# Calculate cost complexity pruning path
path = dt_classifier.cost_complexity_pruning_path(X_train, y_train)
ccp_alphas, impurities = path.ccp_alphas, path.impurities

# Find optimal pruning parameter (alpha)
best_alpha = ccp_alphas[np.argmin(impurities[:-1])]

# Train the post-pruned model with the optimal alpha
dt_pruned = DecisionTreeClassifier(random_state=42, ccp_alpha=best_alpha)
dt_pruned.fit(X_train, y_train)

# create a function for decision rules
def get_decision_rules(tree, feature_names, class_names, node_index=0, path=[]):
    tree_ = tree.tree_
    feature = [feature_names[i] for i in tree_.feature]

    # If the node is a leaf node
    if tree_.children_left[node_index] == -1 and tree_.children_right[node_index] == -1:
        rule = ' AND '.join(path)
        class_id = np.argmax(tree_.value[node_index][0])
        class_name = class_names[class_id]
        print(f"IF {rule} THEN Personal_Loan = {class_name}")
        return

    # If the node is an internal node
    threshold = tree_.threshold[node_index]
    feature_name = feature[node_index]

    # go to the left subtree
    new_path = path + [f"{feature_name} <= {threshold}"]
    get_decision_rules(tree, feature_names, class_names, tree_.children_left[node_index], new_path)

    # go to the right subtree
    new_path = path + [f"{feature_name} > {threshold}"]
    get_decision_rules(tree, feature_names, class_names, tree_.children_right[node_index], new_path)

# Call the function with trained decision tree

from sklearn.metrics import accuracy_score, precision_score, recall_score, f1_score

def get_metrics(model, X_test, y_test):
    y_pred = model.predict(X_test)
    return {
        'accuracy': accuracy_score(y_test, y_pred),
        'precision': precision_score(y_test, y_pred),
        'recall': recall_score(y_test, y_pred),
        'f1_score': f1_score(y_test, y_pred)
    }

# Calculate metrics for each model

The reason is because the pre-pruned model is significantly less complex with a depth of 5 and 17 leaves making it easier to interpret and less likely to overfit. In addition, it has the highest precision which is the most important metric for this project. The pre-pruned model offers the best balance between performance and model simplicity. This makes it more likely to be applicable to new data and easier to explain to stakeholders. Precision measures the quality of positive predictions it measures how often a model correctly predicts the positive class. So, for this objective of predicting if a customer accepts a loan precision is real important because if there is a high precision then that means the model will predict that a customer will accept a loan. In banking you don't want the model to predict false positives because that will hurt the business more that is why Precision is real crucial.

In terms of why the Pre-pruned model is best is because it has the highest precision which is an important metric when it comes to positive predictions. Precision measures the quality of positive predictions it measures how often a model correctly predicts the positive class. So, for this objective of predicting if a customer accepts a loan precision is real important because if there is a high precision then that means the model will predict that a customer will accept a loan. In banking you don't want the model to predict false positives because that will hurt the business more that is why Precision is real crucial. With a precision rate of .96 the bank will be able to predict on a real high level which customers will accept a loan based on the decision rules layed out and this will help bring more business in for them since the margin for error will be significantly low with that high precision rate.
